{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17610910","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17610910"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:37+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:05:37+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16180"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16180","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16180"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.18,0.61,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8871"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71214"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8871","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8871"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16180"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56688"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5442"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8113"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21126"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21128"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71214","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71214"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EBreast milk contains various bioactive components that provide immunological protection to newborn infants. These components include antibodies that help protect against infections during early life.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the predominant immunoglobulin found in breast milk?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["IgG","IgM","IgA","IgD","IgE"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe predominant immunoglobulin in breast milk is \u003Cstrong\u003EIgA\u003C/strong\u003E, specifically in its secretory form. This antibody provides crucial passive immunity to infants, protecting their mucosal surfaces, particularly the gastrointestinal tract.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other immunoglobulins are less suitable for breast milk transmission:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgG\u003C/strong\u003E primarily provides systemic immunity and crosses the placenta during pregnancy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgM\u003C/strong\u003E is too large to be effectively secreted in breast milk\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgD\u003C/strong\u003E functions mainly as an antigen receptor on B cells\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIgE\u003C/strong\u003E is involved in allergic responses and parasitic infections\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESecretory IgA is specially adapted to resist degradation by digestive enzymes and can survive in the infant\u0027s gastrointestinal tract, where it helps prevent the attachment and entry of potentially pathogens.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Secretory IgA is the predominant immunoglobulin in breast milk, providing passive immunity to infants.","IgA in breast milk helps protect the infant\u0027s gastrointestinal tract from pathogens.","Breast milk IgA is specifically adapted to resist degradation by digestive enzymes."],"references":["Ballard O, Morrow AL. Human milk composition: nutrients and bioactive factors. Pediatr Clin North Am. 2013 Feb;60(1):49-74. doi: 10.1016/j.pcl.2012.10.002. PMID: 23178060; PMCID: PMC3586783","Kim SY, Yi DY. Components of human breast milk: from macronutrient to microbiome and microRNA. Clin Exp Pediatr. 2020 Aug;63(8):301-309. doi: 10.3345/cep.2020.00059. Epub 2020 Mar 23. PMID: 32252145; PMCID: PMC7402982","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Biswas SK, Banerjee S, Baker GW, Kuo CY, Chowdhury I. The Mammary Gland: Basic Structure and Molecular Signaling during Development. Int J Mol Sci. 2022 Mar 31;23(7):3883. doi: 10.3390/ijms23073883. PMID: 35409243; PMCID: PMC8998991","Rio-Aige K, Azagra-Boronat I, Castell M, Selma-Royo M, Collado MC, Rodr\u00edguez-Lagunas MJ, P\u00e9rez-Cano FJ. The Breast Milk Immunoglobulinome. Nutrients. 2021 May 26;13(6):1810. doi: 10.3390/nu13061810. PMID: 34073540; PMCID: PMC8230140."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56688"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16180"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/56688"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-17T20:29:13+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-17T20:29:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8871"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71214"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type"